Best location in town. Ideal for couples, business travellers et cetera. In the middle of Amsterdam (really close to everything you could wish for) and still in a relatively quiet spot. The real citybuzz is around the corner and less in front :-)

The space
Many canalhouses are facing just one canal. This one is facing two. One canal in the front and one at the side. Situated at what is called "Little Venice" this light and bright appartment with many windows offers all comfort you'll search for in Amsterdam.

Because the appartment is situated in a bend of the canal, you'll experience an extraordinary view that oversees 5 bridges and over 750 metres (0,5 miles). But above all, the apartment is situated as central as you can be in the city with the famous 9 streets on the corner, the famous 9 bridges in 1 minutes walk and the well known shoppingstreets 'Kalverstraat' and 'Leidschestraat' on the other corner.

There are many, many, really many.
neighborhood_overview: The famous 9 streets are around the corner. The apartment is situated in the middle of the vibrant center of Amsterdam but yet relative quiet. Many (/all) cosy restaurants, pubs, clubs, boutiques, must see things on walking distance.
host_about: I (Ingo) work in Advertising (freelance copywriter), love my girlfriend Marlies, like to travel, like the fun things in life, like design, like cool movies, like all kinds of music (mostly non-commercial), like cars, like (scuba) diving, like new and different cultures, like good food, like to cook, like the summertime, like positive people, like friendships, like hanging out, like Amsterdam, like New York, like Asian countries, like being happy, like water(sports), and so on and so on... Wanna know more likes (or if i even dislike something :-) please contact me.

description:
This charming and bright Amsterdam apartment is my home, I hope you'll feel like it's your home while you're here.

Its full of light and appears to be a perfect start to explore the city by foot or bike.
Due its warm feel, comfortable huge bed and handy kitchen its a perfect place to relax on those moments when you aren't exploring the city.

Please have a look at the reviews for a better understanding.

The space
Located right in the center of Amsterdam is the popular Helmers neighbourhood, we offer this renovated privately owned apartment. It is close (walking distance) to all the interesting things Amsterdam offers you. The apartment is situated at the 3rd floor and accessed via traditional steep Amsterdam stairs. Perfect for couples.

Living in this house gives you a cozy & warm feeling (see photos). Once your inside the house, you will notice the peaceful feeling, but when you step out of the door, energy is all around you

host_about:
You are welcome in our Big Family House! 

So many books because I used to be an Artbook Publishers (Artimo & Veenman Publishers) for many years till 2008. I published lots of great Art books but also Design, Fashion and Architecture books and magazines. 

Since 2008 I am a art curator again. Being the Curator for Contemporary Art at the Keukenhof Castle ( a 17th Century Castle near Amsterdam see: (website hidden)) from 2008-2014 Then i am the owner and curator of SALON/ : an art/fashion/design route in Amsterdam, Cape Town, Aruba, Maastricht and Istanbul beijing etc. Now working on the new space XBANK in W hotel and a new Design Museum. 

We like to share so our house is a warm welcome to lots of people we like to host as guests but also for exhibitions, special dinners, house concerts etc. ( for shows and events  in our place see : (website hidden))

We love to live in the center of Amsterdam. Everything on walking distance. 
Enjoy Amsterdam as a cosy village with the allure of a Metropolis. 

And meet the Family: my partner Angelo ( cultural attache for Aruba in The Hague) and the twins Anna & Helena (20 years)

name: Houseboat on the Amstel
description:
Houseboat on the Amstel, magnificent view, large garden, close to city centre, kayak, SUP, free parking.

The space
The perfect spot, a nice houseboat, big garden and very close to the city center. It has a good kitchen (bulthaup with gaggenau steam oven), living room with large sliding doors and 2,5 bedrooms (one is very small), bathroom, separate toilet and heated floors. The view, the garden, the tropical freshwater aquarium, the feeling of living on water and the neighborhood make it the perfect place for your stay in Amsterdam. We have a great sit-on kayak and a stand-up paddle board. We swim (and jump of the bridge) on nice days in the river; safe and fun.

We have prepared a comprehensive guide to our home, neighborhood and the surrounding area and will leave a few starter items in the fridge for when you arrive. Closets and drawers will be cleaned out so that you can unpack and stay a while.

From one of our guests:
"Please allow
neighborhood_overview: Train, metro, tram, gym, restaurants, shops all within 10 minutes walking. Amsterdam is a great and small city. All is easy to reach with public tranportation, by bike or just take it easy and walk. (website hidden)
host_about:
We, Ilona and Marco have 2 sweet young daughters, Zamaya and Anaiza. Before the girls were born we traveled for 21 months throughout the world. Now with the girls we continue traveling. Have been with them to Thailand (4,5 months), USA/Mexico (2,5 months), Bali/SE Asia (2x3 months), Australia (3 months), Costa Rica (3 months) and thanks to Europa's compact ability had loads of shorter holidays as well. Lots of home-exchanges!!  We love being together and showing them all the beautiful places around the world. They are 2 easily adjusting, well traveled sweeties. Just being together with the family for longer periods of time is high on our list! 
Marco worked as a financial controller before he stopped working when the oldest was born. He worked as a volunteering guide in the Amsterdam Zoo and is currently studying naturopathy. Ilona works as an air traffic controller at Schiphol airport. We are very flexible. Due to my work we can fly easy, cheap and often.

We did 45+ exchanges/airbnb's so far, hope many will follow. In addition to house swapping we rent out our boat as well. We prefer renting it for longer periods at the time, but with a minimum of 2 nights shorter periods are possible as well.

name: Bright and spacious apartment close to Vondelpark!
description:
Welcome to my home! It's bright & spacious in a trendy manner. The apartment is located in a quiet street in a hip area called "Old West" very close to the Vondelpark. Nearby the city centre and around the corner a lot of shops, trendy bars, restaurants and boutiques. Supermarkets within walking distance and the Overtoom; a long street with a lot of trendy stores and public transport which will take you into the centre or to Schiphol airport very quickly.

The space
The apartment is located on the 3rd floor of an old characteristic building (1906) with a sunny balcony.

The space is open with a large fully equipped kitchen, dining room table and comfy living room area. The stairs in the middle of the room lead to the bedroom, which you can close with a hatch door. I'll make sure that you have fresh linnen and towels and storage for your clothes.

There is enough entertainment outside of the apartment, but if you'd prefer a cosy night in, you ca
neighborhood_overview:
You can find the apartment in the middle of the popular Oud-West area, only a short walk away from the beautiful Vondelpark. You can walk to the Leidse Square and the Museum district within 15 minutes.

Oud-West is a trendy neighbourhood, with many coffee places, cool bars & restaurants and trendy boutiques. All of these just a minute away from the apartment. The Wilhelminastraat finds itself right in between the lively streets of the Overtoom, Kinkerstraat and Jan Pieter Heijestraat, yet is surprisingly quiet.

The 'Hallen' including the Foodhallen, Filmhallen and nice Sunday Market is also just around the corner.

The Plantage neighbourhood ( locally known as the Cultural Garden of Amsterdam ) is special, quiet but centrally located. Local bars and cafes now include the restored De Plantage Cafe restaurant attached to the Zoo. Only a few minutes walk away is the Artis Plein where you can sit for free looking at the spoonbills, flamingos and fountain.
Easily accessible by public transport ( Metro-Waterloo Plein : Hortus exit, or trams 9 and 14 from Central Station) we are happy to advise on the best route to reach us. If you are coming by car we can also help as to where to access cheaper out of city centre parking. Paid street parking is also an option. We can advise on nearby bike hire.Its easy to access most of the city centre on foot.

Our children are beginning to leave home but we are used to having people about and enjoy sharing the love of the city with our visitors.

name: Bed&Breakfast 'MS Jantina' Amsterdam
description:
Experience intense living on the houseboat "Jantina", built in 1927. Sustainably heated, insulated and ventilated, but still with an authentic character (low ceilings and narrow doors).
AIRB&B Jantina (16 m2) is Covid19 save and in the back of the ship. The room has a double bed (200 x 160 cm) with two duvets and a private bathroom (towels available). The B&B has its own entrance with. Fridge, kettle, nespresso and tea available in the room. Optional breakfast is served in the wheelhouse.

The space
Seven small portholes fitted with shutters and the skylight let the rising sun come in beautifully in the morning. At night, the water mirrors the moonlight on the ceiling above the bed .The robust steel wall separating the sleeping area from the bathroom once served as a watertight bulkhead and has been restored to its original state by us. The carefully restored antique wooden door gives access to the beautiful bathroom.

A lovely place, overlooking t
neighborhood_overview:
There is a spectacular and wide view of the Markermeer and the picturesque village of Durgerdam is visible on the starboard side. A bike ride to this village and other villages under the smoke of Amsterdam is highly recommended.
The nearest supermarket is less than 15 minutes' walk away and just before that is the largest skate track in the Netherlands. Fascinating to see how the skateboarders from our city enjoy themselves here. Or do you want to try it yourself? IJburg is about the same distance in an easterly direction. With a larger shopping center, restaurants, a pleasant harbor and Blijburg beach. Walking or cycling to Amsterdam East, the most multicultural area of Amsterdam with the well-known daily Dappermarkt, is also very doable. (approx. 45 minutes walk)

At Conscious Hotel Museum Square we think only about your well-being, and that of the planet. This means we make our choices as sustainable as possible, we re-use and recycle and we only serve organic food and drinks. We have biodegradable furniture and use recycled or cradle to cradle materials, to name a few things. We have the best beds so you’ll sleep well, and we like to smile a lot because that makes everyone feel good. We’re super close to the Museum Square and we love this arty environment.

host_about:
We are conscious about the choices we make. That is why there is sustainability in everything that we do, without compromising comfort. And our stylish hotels and restaurants each have their own unique style and story, which makes every visit a special experience. We do it differently by nature.

We have been around for over 10 years now, making us pioneers in eco-friendly tourism.

We do it differently by combining stylish design and playfulness with sustainability, calling it Eco-Sexy. This is felt throughout your entire stay. From small notes in the rooms that tell guests about the recycled furniture and water-saving showers to every bite and drink that are served being fully organic. There is no stopping us delivering the eco choice while maintaining a high level of comfort.

name: Quiet 4p-appt in green area at park in center
description:
Unique place to stay for a maximum of 4 people in the green, quiet part of the centre of Amsterdam. In the middle of the 'Plantage-area', the green neighborhood of Amsterdam. Close to where it all happens (15-20 minutes on foot), but a peaceful and friendly area to stay. Perfect for families with kids.

The space
You stay in a renovated monumental building (150 years old). You have a view on the Wertheimpark, the oldest park of Amsterdam. With four persons you will enjoy the spacious and light apartment, situated in the 'souterrain' (basement) of our home. During summer you can be in the middle of the Gay Pride festivities and during winter you will be able to enjoy the Amsterdam Light Festival and the Illuminade (a special arts and light walking route in our area). And almost all other sights to see are at walking distance (15-20 minutes) or easy to be reached by public transport.

Guest access
You have your own private access to the apartme
neighborhood_overview:
Our neighborhood (the Plantage) is a small green village in the center of Amsterdam. There is a mix of people: students, families, the elderly, tourists, artists and writers. Artis is a one minute walk. In the morning you can hear the monkeys! The Hortus Botanicus is just as close.

De Plantage is an old Jewish neighborhood with several memorial monuments. Our house is located at the Wertheimpark, the oldest park in Amsterdam. Children can play there and you can enjoy a picnic. The oldest center of Amsterdam is a 15-20 minute walk away. Our guests are very enthusiastic about the neighborhood, which is quiet, but very close to the center. Check the reviews!

neighborhood_overview:
Within walking distance is a large supermarket (1 min) and a bathing jetty (1min). It is a child-friendly neighborhood with many playgrounds in each courtyard. Cafes and restaurants can be found at the NDSM hotspot (15 min walk).

This area is called the Bongerd (orchard of apple trees) and is part of the bigger area ‘Tuindorp-Oostzaan’ (garden village). Bongerd means orchard, so all our streetnames are names of different sorts of apples, like our street ‘Kaneelappelstraat’ (apple cinnamon street).This neighbourhood has been built in the last 7 years.

We live very close to the NDSM-wharf, which is in the Top-10 of the hippest area's in Europe. This used to be a harbour. You can still see an old crane at the end of the street, which had been used for building 80% of the houses that are in this area as of the 1950s. Our neighbourhood is trying to preserve & restore the old crane. You can find really good restaurants in the most spectacular places. You can have a par
host_about:
Hello there!

My husband - Frans - and I have been living in Amsterdam for over 10 years. For us it's the most wonderful city to live in!

I'm Belgian and Frans is a Dutchman. Together we've done quite some traveling. We met in Mallorca, lived together in Ghent, Belgium for 3 years, lived in Istanbul, Turkey for 1/2 year, extensively travelled through Italy & Spain and in 2013 we came back from a 1 year trip around South-America. Though having seen all these beautiful places, Amsterdam has stolen our hearts and we can't imagine living anywhere else but here. Cycling through the city, across the bridges and next to the canals always puts a very large smile on our faces! 

We invite you to come and explore all the magic this city has to offer!

Elien & Frans

neighborhood_overview:
The North side of amsterdam is upcoming since a few years. Untill 5 years ago, the place seemed a bit dull, and people from the city centre hardly ever took the ferry to have a look here. Houses were cheap, and therefore a lot of creatives and artists started to move here. Since then the 'jump over the IJ river' has been made and now it is one of the hottest area's in town. Even the new York times wrote about it as one of the world's top 10 hip places in the world.
The area still feels like a village: human scale housing, a lot of green and parks (it is the greenest area in Amsterdam).
The van der Pekbuurt is also still one of the poorest area's in Amsterdam. And a lot of other area's in the North are. But it is getting mixed now, and the mix is a nice one.
People originally living here are real Amsterdam people. If you speak to them, the amsterdam accent is clear. And peak trough windows in the neigbourhoud: A lot of people love to fill up their houses with a lot of di

neighborhood_overview:
The Jordaan is a famous district in the center of Amsterdam. Originally it was a working-class neighborhood, but now the Jordaan is one of the most expensive locations in Amsterdam.

Most of the streets and canals are named after flowers and trees. It is a cosy neighborhood with many traditional cafes, art galleries, modern art and specialty shops and restaurants.

Many houses have inner courtyards, the courtyards were built by rich people for elderly women. There are 3 markets in this district; the Noordermarkt, there is a market at the Westerstraat and at the Lindengracht. Around these areas there are a lot of traditional cafes and bars.

The world famous Anne Frank Huis is located in this district. It is a biographical museum dedicated to Anne Frank, who was a diarist during the Second World War.

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in the middle of the ''De Pijp'' neighborhood. De Pijp is a hip and happening neighbourhood with a large concentration of restaurants, cafés and bars catering to just about every class and taste.

A few places in Amsterdam have undergone the transformation that de Pijp has gone through in the last 20 years. Once considered a claustrophobic workers neighbourhood with small leaky houses, it’s now home to a multitude of creatives, young families and start ups. It's absolutely exploding with the internationally oriented bars and restaurants to cater to them all with the Albert Cuyp (a seemingly never-ending street market) as the beating heart of it all.

The area is intersected by the Ceintuurbaan, leaving its northern half with the charming Sarphatipark and the southern part with its special Japanese shops and restaurants, crowned by the presence of the Okura hotel and its multiple (Japanese) Michelin starred restaurants.

The neares

Welcome to an amazing floating experience in Amsterdam! You will love the cozy and relaxed atmosphere that this 110 year old historical ship has to offer. Our guests enjoy the privacy of a double cabin, the comfort of a fully equipped kitchen, the sophisticated design of our lounge area and a tasty and bounteous breakfast buffet. The ship is located in the IJburg neighborhood and connects to the city center by express tram with departure every 6 minutes. The tram takes 20 min. to get downtown.

The space
You will be staying in one of the 10 private double cabins we have on board. Each cabin has a bunk bed with comfortable mattresses and pillows, a sink with drinking water and an independent heating system. There are 2 toilets and 2 showers on board, which you will be sharing with other guests. Bed linen and towels are provided.

Guest access
Guests are entitled to their private double cabin and can access the toilets, showers, kitchen and lou
neighborhood_overview:
The IJburg residential area is new, actually a group of islands that have been newly created over the last 10 years, on what used to be a swampy coastline. All housing is new, as well as the small harbor that the boat is moored in.
Several restaurants and a supermarket are very nearby, as well as public transportation to the city.
A beach with a very nice bar/diner is also nearby.

Beautiful house with garden from 1897, decorated with lots of art, plants and books!

The house is very close to the Weesperzijde, the beautiful avenue along the river Amstel with many nice cafes and restaurants, a lot of houseboats with pretty gardens and the best sunset view of the city.

The space
The ground and first floor of a beautiful house filled with art, plants, books and a vintage jukebox. Located right by the Amstel, in a beautiful neighbourhood 5 minutes away from the city centre on the metro or 15 minutes by bike.

The cosy living room has a TV (with a Google Chromecast device) and an open kitchen, fully equipped with all necessary cooking utensils, an induction plate, big fridge, oven, espresso machine (and complimentary coffee), dishwasher, all sorts of herbs and many Dutch and English cookbooks. Outside of the kitchen is a beautiful private garden, which gets lots of sunlight.

Up the stairs, you will find a spacious
neighborhood_overview:
The house is situated in Weesperzijde, between De Pijp and the very trendy Eastern part of Amsterdam. It is home to a variety of exciting bars and restaurants such as Bam Bao, Rijsel, Drover's Dog and many more. Volkshotel is on the same street as the house and has a rooftop bar / restaurant, as well as a secret basement bar. The Student Hotel is a two minute walk from the studio - there, you can have cocktails, pizzas and play a game of pool or ping pong. Both hotels also frequently have a variety of events on!

There is a supermarket (Albert Heijn) located 5 minutes away by foot, as well as numerous bike rental shops.

name: SWEETS Hotel Zeilstraatbrug
description:
A cosy bridge house on the Amstel river in a vibrant neighbourhood near the popular Albert Cuyp market. The interior is divided into two floors with bathroom facilities on the lower level and a playful mezzanine bedroom above. Stroll to local cafés in the fashionable neighbourhood of De Pijp or take a walk into the centre of Amsterdam along the Amstel river (25 minutes).

The space
From 1912 to 2017 the Nieuwe Amstelbrug bridge house accommodated the city’s bridge keepers. In 2017 the bridge house started a new chapter as one of SWEETS hotel's 28 hotel rooms. As with every SWEET, Nieuwe Amstelbrug’s interior is inspired by its architectural history.

Architect 1912: Johan Melchior van der Mey
Architect 2017: Space&Matter
Architectural Style: Early Amsterdam School
Bridge Type: Bascule Bridge

The Nieuwe Amstelbrug (bridge) was designed in 1903 by Hendrik Leguyt with Hendrik Petrus Berlage acting as aesthetic advisor. The bridge h
neighborhood_overview: Bridge house Nieuwe Amstelbrug is situated just outside the city centre, adjacent to neighbourhood 'De Pijp', one of the most popular areas in Amsterdam. Take a stroll on the famous Albert Cuypmarkt in the morning,  grab some lunch at the end and visit the museums around Museum Square with renewed energy. Don't feel like walking? Hop on the tram, train or bus – all around the corner of Nieuwe Amstelbrug. Check out our city guide for more recommendations!
host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

description:
Actually, I wanted to spend even more on each room, the furniture, the decoration and the many details... my husband and I just didn't seem to be on the same page. But I love my little hideaway in the middle of Amsterdam. Our neighbours in this place full of history are all native ones. Lawyers, midwives, judges, journalists and creative people live here close together - right in the city centre and yet away from the noise and bustle of the unbelievably many tourists.

The space
I want to give you a sense of "home" in these rooms. Modern, high-quality furnishings, designer pieces and especially many small details selected with love. Whenever I have found great pieces at a flea market again, I hope that you as guests will enjoy them.

In addition to the large terrace for all guests on the second floor, there is also the communal kitchen on the ground floor right at the entrance (then you do not have to carry the groceries far!) There is a record player -
neighborhood_overview:
Living by the canal - that is a dream for many. In the past, however, this was considered frowned upon and not classical enough. Therefore the canal was filled up around 16th century. A beautiful park in the middle of the city was created - and still is today. Large trees that provide shade in summer and absorb the sounds of the city.
I love the Cafe Slijterij Oosterling (50m from us). Open since 1877, this is probably one of the most authentic places in Amsterdam. Time seems to stand still here. If you are hungry, you can get delicious sandwiches, burgers, salads or freshly caught fish in the Brasserie Nel (400m). If you prefer self-catering and our shared kitchen, the supermarket is only 70m away.

neighborhood_overview: Oud-Zuid is a well-to-do neighbourhood in the centre of Amsterdam. It is a largely residential district, characterised by the 1920's Dutch art-deco style housing, called Amsterdamse School. A number of the city's famous museums, such as Van Gogh, Stedelijk and Rijksmuseum are housed here, as is the Royal Dutch Concerthall, home to the world-renowned Concertgebouw Orkest. The area also has ample options for wining and dining, through its characteristic coffee houses, (brown) cafes and the many restaurants and it has several boutique shopping streets, including our own address, that attract high-heeled shoppers from around the country.

neighborhood_overview: The Jordaan is possibly the most famous neighbourhood in the Netherlands. description:
Five windows overlooking the most beautiful canal junction in the historic city centre make this modern minimalist appartment in a 17th century monument a most wanted location to enjoy Amsterdam at its very best!

The space
The appartment (60 m2) with the typical triangle shape of the corner house is with an open floor plan around a central walk in closet deviding the living room with the big book case and the (gas-)fireplace from the small dining room with adjanct kitchen featuring all modern coocking comfort (combi overn/microwave, fridge, ceramic cooking field, etc). Living room and dinig/cooking area are facing the prestigious Herengracht with a unique 5 windows in a row. The sleeping room with a double bed, a work desk and the small bathroom (shower, sink, toilet) are oriented towards the Beulingstraat.

neighborhood_overview:
H401 is situated at a historic canal district in the most prestigious part of Amsterdam, right in-between the 'Gouden Bocht' (golden bent) and The Nine Streets - De Negen Straatjes, one of the city’s most delightful shopping areas. These picturesque streets straddle the 17th Century canals from the Singel to the Prinsengracht.
Spend a fabulous day wandering from one to the next exploring the designer boutiques, art galleries, jewellers, gift shops, fashion shops and specialist businesses - there are plenty of great bars, cafes and restaurants to refresh you along the way... And last but not least: all famous museums are within walking distance.
host_about:
H401 is the name of a 17th century canal house in the very centre of Amsterdam at one of the most beautiful canal conjunctions. The house has a stunning history as a hiding place during WWII, but other than the Anne Frank house the building is still used for living and working . In their gallery and studio space H401 features a unique high end cultural programme based on the history of the house that has always been a magnet for artists, writers and people on the move. Castrum Peregrini was the code name during the war and literally translates as 'castle of the pilgrim'. The original hiding place is still preserved and the various floors and spaces represent the houses vibrant history since the 1940s.

We are three friends, Michael, Frans and Lars that run H401 today and we also live in the building, which is big enough to be a universe in itself. We offer three luxurious independent guest appartments, both recently restored in a minimalist manner, with a stunning view to the canal in the front  facing a row of historic 17th century gables and the monumental Krijtberg Church in the back. The rooms offer the unique experience of a historic place with contemprary comfort (state of the art beds, linen, towels etc) The appartments offer equiped kitchens and coffee, tea, and some simple breakfast incredients. Though the accomodations are situated at a quite part of the famous 'gouden bocht' of the Herengracht, the lively and fashionable nine streets are just a stone's throw away; they offer stylish cafes, bars, shops, lunch and diner possibilities. All famous sites and musea are walking distance. Amsterdam at its very best!

host_about:
Welcome at Mi BnB, our B&B in Amsterdam West! We started in May 2017 and have had lots of guests from all over the world since then.

Mi BnB offers 2 simple rooms, the larger "Nice Room" on the 1st floor and the "Cozy Room" our tiny room on the ground floor. 

Each room has it's own small private bathroom, a smart tv,  coffee & tea facilities and a fridge. The 2 rooms share the front door and a small hall.

The B&B is in our family home in a nice, quiet, green neighbourhood, with excellent public transport around the corner. It is only half an hour to the city centre and all the tourist attractions are easy to reach by bus, tram or bike!

In Amsterdam it is only allowed to run a B&B when the owner lives in the house as well. So we are also living in the house with our children and our German Sheppard.

Please don't expect silence! At night it is quiet in general after 22h.

I love to meet new people from over the world and to speak foreign languages like English, Spanish, Italian and a little Portuguese, French and German.

We rent bikes for 10 euro per bike per day. 

Hope to meet you soon! 
Michèle  - Mi BnB

neighborhood_overview:
During The Golden Age the Watergraafsmeer was the polder where merchants built their out of town residents, and some of that airy, stately atmosphere is still contained. Frankendael, now turned over in a great restaurant (do eat lunch on their wonderfull terrace in summer) on the Middenweg, is the one example that has survived. There's a wonderfull garden and town park adjacent.
You don't even have to go to the citycenter to spend a wonderfull time in Amsterdam: the Watergraafsmeer (and the other eastern parts of Amsterdam) is a very popular neighbourhood, full of hipster cafés and trendy restaurants, a list of which we will provide. You can look for great architecture at the nearby Indische buurt, and the Eastern Islands. There are great parks to relax and sport close by: the kid friendly Frankendael, the Flevopark (great for running) and Oosterpark.
For your daily groceries: the C. Huijgensplein is 5 minutes from our home, the Middenweg just about 10. Here you can find supe

We love to welcome you in our large and comfortable home in Amsterdam and are more then happy to show you the best musea, cafés, restaurants, public parks, vintage shops, clubs and cinema's in the city.When we travel ourselves we also prefer to stay in privately owned apartments or houses because, especially with  children, it is comforting to have your home away from home. Also we like to meet new people!
Italy is definitely our favorite country, but we also loved exploring Paris, Brittany, London, Bali, Barcelona and Catalunya. Other family favorites include food, wine and football.
We have an optimistic spirit and take excellent care of the places we stay. We are confident you will treat ours likewise.

neighborhood_overview:
This apartment is located in the "Hoofddorpplein" neighbourhood, which is located in the district "Amsterdam-Zuid".

The neighborhood was built in the twenties. The characteristic architectural style can be found everywhere in the streetscape, such as the eccentric housing porticoes and the pointed corner towers.

Two beautiful parks, Vondelpark and Rembrandtpark, are just around the corner: 5 minutes by bike or 15 minutes walk.
In the summer, you can relax (and even swim!) at the Stadiongracht or in Park Schinkeleilanden.

This quiet neighborhood is popular with families, students and couples. It is very conveniently located near the station Amsterdam-Zuid where all train, metro, and tram connections are available. the building is on an industrial area so you have no problem with neighbours. yet you are close to the centre with public transport ( two stops) or by ferry or by bike .
don't go with your car to the centre because there you will pay €5,00 per hour to park.
There is a chinees take-away next door. there is a good thay restaurant 100meters away. there is a snackbar / sandwich shop 50 m. and next to the snackbar is a coffeeshop for all typical Amsterdam smokeries.
There is a liqour store at the corner next to the snackbar. the bakery is crossing the street from the liquor store. there you will also find a pizzaria take-away and a good surinam restaurant. more to the right from the bakery there is a turkisch supermarket for all vegetables, meat, cheeses, olives and all good stuff. to the right of the turisch supermarket you will find the daily market ( on wednesday friday , saturday) and the dutch supermarket the Deen (best price) and the Albert Heijn.(more expencive)
host_about:
ik vind het leuk om creatief bezig te zijn en om de dingen mooi te maken. Ik heb dan ook al mijn creativiteit gestopt in het ontwerpen en inrichten van mijn appartementen. ik ontwerp zelf de oliedrum-keukenkasten . en kroonluchters van aanhangwagens bijvoorbeeld.
ik probeer altijd om iets te gebruiken wat een andere functie had en vorm dat om tot een nieuw gebruik. 
 verder ben ik gek op reizen . ben al vaak in Afrika geweest en wil eigenlijk zo vaak mogelijk op reis zijn . maar nu houd de passie voor het verhuren van mijn 3 appartementen me hier bezig en vind ik het leuk om gasten te verwelkomen en hun enthousiasme te zien als ze binnen komen.

name: New! Modern & cozy studio at Eastern Docklands | 2P
description:
Right in Amsterdam’s Eastern Docklands near ‘Het IJ’ lies Eastend Room. You'll be in the city centre within a few minutes! Eastend Room is a luxurious studio with its own entrance and terrace. The studio has a great atmosphere, so you will feel right at home! There is no kitchen, but you'll find coffee/tea facilities in the studio. I am sure you will have a great time in this studio while staying in Amsterdam!

The space
The location of The Eastend Room in this quiet, popular and architecturally attractive district provides an excellent base for exploring the Amsterdam city centre and its attractions. Also the neighborhood itself has enough to offer to make a visit to the capital of the Netherlands worthwhile.

You will have amazing views over the IJ at the Eastern Docklands! The studio itself is very modern and has a lot of natural light. It is accommodated with a comfortable king sized bed, where you really get to rest after a long day of sightseeing
neighborhood_overview:
The Eastend room is situated in one of the newest neighbourhoods of Amsterdam, on the island Sporenburg in the Eastern Docklands. The former docklands have been transformed into an attractive, modern residential area with a mix of old and modern architecture. The area is completely surrounded by water and has a dinstinctive look. See: (URL HIDDEN)

Although the district is located close to the busy city centre of Amsterdam, it is an oasis of calm. In warmer weather you will find residents sitting outside at the door. Children play in the streets and there is no through traffic.

Stops for public traffic (bus and tram) are just a 3 minute walk. By express tram you are only three stops away from the Amsterdam Central train station.
host_about:
I have lived my whole live in Amsterdam and for the last 8 years in this new part; the old docklands.  This neighborhood is a mix of old and new buildings, surrounded by water, and stunning contemporary architecture.  It’s a very relaxed, green and hip part of Amsterdam. Children still play on the street and people sit outside on the pavement in front of their house when the weather is nice. You will find lot of shops here and many nice restaurants (some of them with a terrace on the waterfront). After a visit to the noisy and hectic city center it’s great to return to the quiet, peaceful and relaxed atmosphere of my neighborhood.
Can’t wait to welcome you in Eastendroom. 

Truus

Iamb&b is taking care of my apartment while i'm gone!

neighborhood_overview:
The Jordaan is a neighbourhood of the city of Amsterdam, Netherlands. It is part of the borough of Amsterdam-Centrum. The area is bordered by the Lijnbaansgracht canal to the west, the Prinsengracht to the east, the Brouwersgracht to the north and the Leidsegracht to the south. The former canal Rozengracht (now filled in) is the main traffic artery through the neighbourhood.Originally a working-class neighbourhood, the Jordaan has become one of the most expensive, upscale locations in the Netherlands. It is home to many art galleries, particularly for modern art, and is also dotted with speciality shops and restaurants. Markets are held regularly at Noordermarkt, the Westerstraat (the Lapjesmarkt textile market) and Lindengracht.

Rembrandt spent the last years of his life in the Jordaan, on the Rozengracht canal. He was buried in the Westerkerk church, at the corner of Rozengracht and Prinsengracht, just beyond the Jordaan. The Anne Frank House, where Anne Frank went into hi

neighborhood_overview:
Spiegelkwartier

The Spiegelkwartier is the Art and Antiques district in Amsterdam.
Here you’ll find more than 70 antiques dealers and art galleries, together offering a resplendent array of fine historical objects, classic and contemporary art, and exotic folk art.
You will find also restaurants, casual eateries and cosy cafés on almost every corner.
The Spiegelkwartier is located between the Herengracht and the Rijksmuseum.

www.spiegelkwartier.nl

Museum Quarter

The Amsterdam Museum Quarter is home to the three most important museums in the Netherlands: the Rijksmuseum, the Stedelijk Museum and the Van Gogh Museum.
It also houses the majestic Concertgebouw and some superb cafés and restaurants.
With its large grassy open area, the Museumplein offers plenty of room to have a picnic or just relax. The Museum Quarter even has its own indoor swimming pool.

neighborhood_overview: Our neighbourhood is in the sunny side of the river IJ that crosses Amsterdam. Amsterdam's north side is undergoing a rapid transformation of gentrification where industry, varying from wharves to small scale car shops, is making place for houses. Our specific neighborhood has been residential since the early 20th century. Although in our street there are three older farms, one going back as far as the 17th century. It has a very cosy and private feeling, with many gardens, an old dyke, a canal and it still has a certain rural atmosphere. But as said before; Central Sation is 15 minutes by bike, from there on you easily walk or bike almost anywhere in Amsterdam since it is a very compact city. You can obviously also connect to almost all trains, trams, busses and metro.

description:
The space
At The Tire Station we think only about your well-being, and that of the planet. We have solar panels on our roof, we reuse and recycle, and we only serve organic food and drinks.

We have the best beds so you’ll sleep well, and we like to smile a lot because that makes everyone feel good. We’re super close to the Vondelpark, so you can enjoy the green environment any time, even in this bustling city called Amsterdam.

Eco-Sexy. Big Smiles.

- Parking for 1 car included
- Free wifi
- Huge double bed
- Flat-screen TV
- Desk

neighborhood_overview: Conscious Hotel The Tire Station is located right next to the Vondelpark. By bike you only have to cruise through the park and you find yourself at the Leidse square in no time. In this area there are the most famous museums of Amsterdam, like the Rijksmuseum, the Van Gogh Museum and the Stedelijk Museum. Trams directly bring you into the center, the tram stop is only a few walking minutes away from our front door. You can get to the airport in about 20 minutes by public transport.
host_about:
We are conscious about the choices we make. That is why there is sustainability in everything that we do, without compromising comfort. And our stylish hotels and restaurants each have their own unique style and story, which makes every visit a special experience. We do it differently by nature.

We have been around for over 10 years now, making us pioneers in eco-friendly tourism.

We do it differently by combining stylish design and playfulness with sustainability, calling it Eco-Sexy. This is felt throughout your entire stay. From small notes in the rooms that tell guests about the recycled furniture and water-saving showers to every bite and drink that are served being fully organic. There is no stopping us delivering the eco choice while maintaining a high level of comfort.

name: Private family townhouse with sunny back-garden
description:
The space
Our house is in the "Watergraafsmeer" (east); a very desirable and the most trendy area just minutes from the center of Amsterdam. It's all happening in our hoods.

The architecture is just beautiful with houses built between 1900 and 1927. Our house is build in 1910 and in the most lovely, wide and quite street of Amsterdam. The houses in this street are unique. Not only because of the architecture, but also because they are all 'private houses' which means: no neighbors above or under you (most houses in Amsterdam have at least 4/5 stories).

The neighborhood is the greenest area in Amsterdam, lots of trees and parks (3 within walking distance). Child friendly, wide pavements. On one hand quiet but at the other with all the ammenities required - shops, supermarkets and grocery stores, bakeries and butchery are within 2 minutes walk. There are at least a dozen good (and trendy) restaurants in this area.

neighborhood_overview: You will be staying in the seventeenth-century canal ring area of Amsterdam. Which is on the Unesco’s World Heritage list. Within only a few minutes walking distance you will find, Dam square, the Anne Frank house and Amsterdam’s largest shopping area. The B&B is located in the 9 streets area of the canal ring. The quaint and quirky streets that straddle Amsterdam’s grandest canals form the city’s most photogenic micro-neighbourhood. Known to locals as De Negen Straatjes or ‘The Nine Streets’, this special neighbourhood is full to bursting with vintage and designer shopping, speciality stores and cosy cafés. Because of the big windows a lot of light is allowed to enter the room and give you a chance to take a look at the gardens of the typical Amsterdam homes and even a glance at the Westertoren. Anne Frank wrote in her diary that she could see the tower of the Westerkerk (the church) and hear the bells chiming.
host_about:
Whether you are visiting Amsterdam for the first time or you have visited it before, you will always
find something new in this city full of history. Let us introduce you to this magnificent place in
another way!

We are Maria and Aurora. We met years ago in this same amazing and fabulous city, a city where
dreams come true. Here's something about us too:
I am Maria and I am an aspiring illustrator and I am also a mother. I have a Master Degree in plastic arts , fine arts and art history. After spending time abroad, I decided to stay and live in Holland. Apart from my love for art, I have always dreamed of having a small hotel where I can meet interesting people. What could be better than to be in such a fabulous and artistic city as Amsterdam! I have been away from this wonderful city and country for a short time. But it didn't take long before I came back to Amsterdam to rediscover it. Anyone who has been to Amsterdam one time, always comes back!

I am Aurora and I am a fashion branding manager and PR expert. Fashion is my passion. I have more than 15 years experience in the fashion retail industry and B2B events. I have developed several PR activities for fashion showrooms, international designers, brands, individual press shows and shows for fashion platforms. In addition to my professional love for fashion, I, as a mother, love home comfort and want to pass this love on to you and make you feel at home.

neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam's Jordaan is probably the most famous neighbourhood in the Netherlands.
The Jordaan is nothing but highlights. Maze-like streets offer hidden courtyards, cafés (traditional but also trendy), art galleries and pleasantly noisy neighbours. One also has access to some of the more scenic outdoor markets in the country. In particular, Noordermarkt has a flea market on Monday mornings and an organic farmer's' market on Saturdays. There are many more modern, trendy bars around Noordermarkt and along Westerstraat and Rozengracht. The side-streets that run south of Westerstraat have recently developed into a strong culinary district with some of the city’s more highly regarded restaurants.

neighborhood_overview:

neighborhood_overview:
Away from the crowded, touristy streets, but at only 10 minutes from the city centre you find this nice, safe and quiet neighbourhood. A good night sleep is guaranteed!

Amsterdam North is a very booming area with exclusive restaurants, bars like Eye, Pllek, Noorderlicht, Café De Ceuvel and many more.

Around the corner is a park and many nice play yards for children.

Around the corner there are a few little stores to buy groceries (Sneeuwbalstraat & Azaleastraat) and a bio store at Kamerfoeliestraat.
Also there are a few restaurants. The two Thai places at Kamperfoeliestraat have delicious food. Two blocks from the house there is bakery Isken to buy delicious bread and pasteries.
By bike, car or public transport you can go to the bigger shopping areas in North like Buikslotermeerplein and Banne shopping mall.

Also there is a local market on every wednesday, friday and saturday at Mosplein (10 minutes walking distance).

neighborhood_overview: De Pijp district is one of the most cosmopolitan and vibrant districts of Amsterdam. Formerly a working class quarter built to ease the overpopulated Jordaan in the 19th century and to house laborers, de Pijp as we Amsterdammers know it today is without doubt a melting pot of cultures and nationalities. You can indulge yourself for hours in Amsterdam’s lively Latin Quarter, with its colorful mix of cuisines, terraces and convivial cafés. From the beautiful landscaped gardens of Sarphatipark to the famous Albert Cuypmarkt street market, De Pijp oozes beatnik flair from every angle. Our apartment is on a quiet residential street in the New Pijp, around the corner from Van Woustraat, where you will find cafes, restaurants, supermarkets, local shops and great tram connections. The heart of the city and RAI convention centre are both reachable in less than 15 minutes by tram.

To our guests we offer both touristic information as well as tips for visiting hidden local gems.

neighborhood_overview:
Amsterdam's Jordaan is probably the most famous neighbourhood in the Netherlands.
The Jordaan is nothing but highlights. Maze-like streets offer hidden courtyards, cafés (traditional but also trendy), art galleries and pleasantly noisy neighbours. One also has access to some of the more scenic outdoor markets in the country. In particular, Noordermarkt has a flea market on Monday mornings and an organic farmer's' market on Saturdays. There are many more modern, trendy bars around Noordermarkt and along Westerstraat and Rozengracht. The side-streets that run south of Westerstraat have recently developed into a strong culinary district with some of the city’s more highly regarded restaurants.

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located really close to the Jordaan Area. The Jordaan district is the city center of Amsterdam, known by its beautiful houses, nice restaurants and shops. The canals of Amsterdam are located here as well.

In the Jordaan, there are several markets you can visit. Every Monday, there is a flea market at the Noordermarkt. It is the perfect spot to buy Dutch plates, pots and linen. They are also selling clothes and accessories. For a foodmarket, you can go to the Lindenmarkt at the Lindengracht on Saturdays, to the Westerstraat market on Mondays or to the Biological foodmarket at the Noordermarkt on Saturdays.

The Westertoren is one of the landmarks of the Jordaan. It's really worth to visit and climb! Also close by: Anne Frank Huis, Dam, Royal Palace.

Nice to know: each of the streets is named after a flower.

The space
The house has three bedrooms (one on the ground floor, two on the second floor); a big fully equipped kitchen with dining table on the ground floor; a large, sunny living room on the first floor with a baby grand piano, another dining table and a large international library; three toilets (one on each floor), two showers, and one bathtub in the bright second floor bathroom. There is a balcony off the living room. One bedroom has a kingsize bed, one bedroom has two children’s beds and one bedroom has a queensize bed and a children’s bed.

NB. There is no t.v. in the house! But there is a very fast internet connectio
neighborhood_overview: The house is located in a quiet and very green family neighbourhood. There are two big supermarkets a 5 minute walk away (Jumbo foodmarkt and Dirk), and several nice restaurants and cafés within walking distance. (Such as Hotel de Goudfazant, Hangar, Eye, Cafe Keppler, Mok, Cafe Modern, the brewery cafe Oedipus and the famous fish restaurant Stork.) There are also two cinemas within walking distance (Eye and FC Hyena).

name: SWEETS hotel Buiksloterdraaibrug
description:
Situated on a cycle route in a rustic setting with a view directly over a tiny lake in Amsterdam north. Your neighbours are the local swans. Picturesque Dutch character houses line the street and a postcard-perfect 18th-century windmill is within walking distance. Enjoy a picnic on your private lake-side lawn in summer. In winter this bridge house is a romantic and cosy hide-out. Buiksloterdraaibrug is a perfect overnight stop for cyclists on the LF7 cycle route.

The space
From 1984 to 2017 bridge house Buiksloterdraaibrug accommodated the city’s bridge keepers. In 2017 the bridge house started a new chapter as one of SWEETS hotel's 28 hotel rooms. As with every SWEET, Buiksloterdraaibrug’s interior is inspired by its architectural history.

Architect 1984: Ingenieursbureau Amsterdam (IBA)
Architect 2017: Space&Matter
Architectural Style: Structuralism
Bridge Type: Swing Bridge

The bridge house at Buiksloterdraaibrug (bridge) o
neighborhood_overview: Buiksloterdraaibrug is located in Amsterdam North - a neighbourhood that has become increasingly popular over the past few years. With free ferries crossing the river IJ and the new North-South metro line up and running, it now is faster and easier than ever to get to Amsterdam centre. But why would you, if there's so much to do and see in Buiksloterdraaibrug's vicinity? The relaxing Noorderpark is right next to your bridge house, and a bunch of restaurants and cafés are within walking distance. Check out our city guide for more recommendations!
host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

name: Home at the Park
description:
This B&B is located on the ground floor of a characteristic and solid mansion built around 1900. It's located right at the Oosterpark with easy access to all Amsterdam has to offer. This family friendly B&B with rear yard has two floors with the private area containing 2 bedrooms, bathroom and separate toilet. Guests can use the game room with pool and football table and garden room with many boardgames. There is also a private outside seating area which is rare for Amsterdam.

The space
The B&B is in a beautiful apartment overlooking the Oosterpark. High ceilings and many beautiful details, and combined with a modern look.

The house has a beautiful Oak floor and all is connected to the garden at the rear of the house. It has two bedrooms on the ground floor with floor heating where the new bathroom is situated. In summer, the souterrain stays very cool.
It's a great family stay or for 2 couples.

neighborhood_overview:
East of Amsterdam is a hip and edgy neighbourhood. It's a lot more authentic to Amsterdam and the locals than some other areas. It has many nice cafés and places to eat.
The center, Amstel and Central Station and De Zuidas are quickly and easily accessible. Shops for daily groceries (and more) at the Linnaeusweg, Middenweg and Beukenplein are right around the corner. There is a market for fresh and cheap produce 6 days a week (Dappermarkt) close by. You can walk to the Amstel and of course the Oosterpark which is right across the street. You can cycle to the center or De Pijp in just 10 minutes. The Amstel is 5 minutes by bike, the Tropenmuseum is a 5 minute walk through the park, as is Artis (city Zoo).

name: SWEETS hotel Sluis Haveneiland
description:
If you are looking for a hotel room with a view in Amsterdam, this is it! Located in upcoming neighbourhood IJburg, bridge house 'Sluis Haveneiland' has the most magical view across the IJ lake. Watch sailing boats entering and leaving the harbour through the lock next to your bridge house, and enjoy sunbathing on the jetty.

Directly behind Sluis Haveneiland, a ferry leaves for Fort Pampus and Castle Muiderslot. Tram 26 takes you from Sluis Haveneiland to Amsterdam Central Station (30 minutes).

The space
From 2009 to 2017, bridge house Sluis Haveneiland accommodated the city’s bridge keepers. It started a new chapter in 2017 as one of SWEETS hotel’s 28 hotel rooms. As with every SWEET, Sluis Haveneiland’s interior is inspired by its architectural history.

Architect 2009: Quist Wintermans
Architect 2017: Space&Matter
Architectural Style: Contemporary
Bridge Type: Lock

Because IJburg, Amsterdam’s most recent expansion
neighborhood_overview: Consisting of multiple artificial islands that are connected by bridges over canals, the city’s most recent expansion area ‘IJburg’ still feels like the real Amsterdam. Presumably because of its amazing views – especially during sunrise and sunset – the neighbourhood is rapidly growing more popular and numerous trendy boutiques, classy restaurants and stylish clubs set up shop here, many of them attracting residents from all over Amsterdam. All in all there’s much to do on the island itself, but if you feel like visiting other areas in Amsterdam, tram 26 takes you directly to Amsterdam Central Station in about 30 minutes.

neighborhood_overview:
review of New York Times:

FOOD HALL FAME, 2 P.M.

To be a cutting-edge European capital these days, having an impressive indoor food hall is practically a prerequisite. Enter Amsterdam’s Foodhallen, which opened in a former tram depot in 2014 with about two dozen stalls, many occupied by well-known local businesses. For lunch, hit the highlights, starting with De BallenBar’s truffle bitterballen (traditional Dutch croquettes) and a local craft beer like the chile-and-coriander-infused Thai Thai Tripel from Oedipus Brewing. Then proceed to Viet View for a stupendous banh mi with caramelized pork belly with cucumber, pickled carrots and daikon. Finish with a drink at the gin-and-tonic bar, where the made-in-Holland Vording’s Gin is served in a Spanish-style goblet garnished with red-apple slices and a cinnamon stick. Lunch for two, about €30.
host_about: Hi I'm Noor and living with my 14 year old son here. I am a foodstylist and also a flight attendant which means I travel around the world, getting inspiration and get to know other cultures. Very fond of Amsterdam and my place, so when I am away I want to share my place and tips at this great location with travellers who also love food and local places. When I'm on holidays myself that's my fav. Way of traveling: staying through airbnb at people's places!

neighborhood_overview:
The apartment is located in de so called ''Indische Buurt''. It is a neighbourhood filled with cosy restaurants, cinema etc. and all kinds of other shops are nearby.
The Dappermarkt is one of the country’s oldest - and best - outdoor markets. It forms the multicultural heart of the neighbourhood along with the hip and happening Javastraat, which once only provided every manner of global grocery but is now beginning to feature more upscale cafes and terraces. One of the city’s largest general hospitals, OLVG, is also located here. Two stellar city parks, Oosterpark and Flevopark, provide quick escape from the relatively busy streets. Besides many cheap ethnic eateries and supermarkets, the area is attracting much more higher-end cafes and restaurants who are often reinventing many of the area’s industrial monuments. On sunny days, the parks and terraces are filled with locals.

Amsterdam East is rising as a trendy neighborhood, still 'safe' from the touristy crowds of the center.

At the lively Beukenplein (around the corner) try some delicious Thai cuisine, shop for the best wine and cheese in town at Erik's Delicatessen, have a flower-drawn cappuccino at Koffee Bru or send your postcards from the post office. For a 360° view of Amsterdam, a meal, a drink or live music, go to restaurant/club Canvas on the rooftop terrace of the Volkshotel, a three-minute walk from our place.

Go jogging at the nearby Oosterpark, a beautiful park that houses the Tropen Museum, one of Europe’s leading ethnographic museums. The permanent and temporary exhibitions display (art) objects, photographs, music and film from non-western cultures. We love their interactive exhibitions and programs for children of 6 to 13 years of age.

Either walking along the Amstel River, taking a bike or the tram you're within a stone's throw of busy central Amsterdam

neighborhood_overview:
Welcome to De Pijp.
It’s one of the older neighbourhoods of Amsterdam. It has a lot of nice coffee places to go, trendy boutiques, shops and bars.

De Pijp is brimming with fantastic (typical Dutch) cafés, restaurants, coffee shops and bars. Of course, a visit to Amsterdam wouldn’t be the same without a trip to the famous Albert Cuypmarket, flanked by over 100 shops. If you wander down Albert Cuypstraat, Gerard Doustraat and Ferdinand Bolstraat, the main streets in de Pijp, you'll find many exotic and authentic Syrian, Moroccan, Surinamese restaurants, to name but a few, and a typical Amsterdam pub is located on almost every corner. Also in abundance are the Islamic butchers, Surinamese, Spanish, Indian and Turkish delicatessens and grocery stores.

It's easy to find your way in this area!

neighborhood_overview: Located on the Western Isles, three islands in the centre of Amsterdam, the Zoutkeetsgracht offers you a peaceful place to escape the energy of downtown Amsterdam. After the Second World War, the neighbourhood was rediscovered by various artists and has since then transformed into an appealing living- and working neighbourhood. The shipyards give the place a unique maritime atmosphere. Go for a walk alongside the impressive warehouses and be led towards a variety of trendy restaurants and unique shops that are part of the Western Isles.
host_about:
YAYS Group is an established serviced apartment provider managing 15 aparthotels in Amsterdam, The Hague, the Paris metropolitan area, and Antwerp under the lifestyle brands YAYS (fully serviced aparthotels) and by YAYS (serviced apartments with partially self-serviced solutions). 
Each of the 500 YAYS Group apartments is stylish, spacious, fully equipped, and located in a convenient area. A turn-key living space ready for comfortable short to long stays for leisure and business guests alike, and a base for urban exploration made easier by the YAYS Insiders. With outstanding local knowledge and a talent for sharing it, the YAYS Insiders are more than ordinary hotel staff. They are local experts ready to help every guest to explore beyond the beaten tourist track and unlock the treasures hidden in the local neighbourhood. 
A YAYS Group serviced apartment is a home away from home that sets you on the inside track to local living.

neighborhood_overview:
Residences Old Centre is located on Amsterdam’s Westelijke Eilanden (western islands), a unique and quiet part of the city centre of Amsterdam.

The Westelijke Eilanden are three small islands in the city centre of Amsterdam. Together they form a pictorial, little neighbourhood with plenty of places where you’ll be surprised by its absolute beauty. This once old shipyard area is now a great place to stroll around and experience the best of the old parts of Amsterdam. Expect beautiful old warehouse buildings, small cafes, art galleries and a absolute local feeling in this magnificent downtown area. Although this area is in the city centre it has not been discovered by troops of tourist.

In case you need us to arrange bikes for you, or public transport cards feel free to ask us. We can easily arrange this for our guests.

neighborhood_overview:
Hip places, green spaces and diverse faces. Ethnically diverse and strikingly spacious, Amsterdam East (Oost) is known for its wide streets lined by monumental 19th-century buildings, as well as its vibrant cultural mix. With plenty of opportunities for shopping, eating and drinking, the area boasts an exciting selection of trendy clubs, traditional Turkish bakeries, Surinamese supermarkets and Middle Eastern lunchrooms as well, of course, as the beautiful Oosterpark and the majestic Tropenmuseum.
In addition to plenty of parks, there are also quite a few places to visit and things to do. Have you been to Artis Zoo yet? In the summer Artis also hosts weekly concerts. be sure to also visit the world’s first microbe museum: Micropia. Or check out Amsterdam’s beautiful Hortus Botanicus, one of the oldest botanical gardens in the world.

host_about:
First of all thanks for your curiosity! My name is Sander and since 10 years I lecture economics at university. Before that I worked for several companies in the sales department. 

In between jobs I backbacked through Asia, Central and South America for 1 year, so you can imagine my interest for travelling! I have experienced the most amazing things in which people always made the difference. In that perspective my long time friends describe me (yes I've asked!) as an adventurous, social, sincere, funny, energetic guy that loves good wine and good food in good company. 

After renting out my apartment for a few years I can honestly say that I enjoy hosting people and advising them on what to do while they are here. Since this is my personal home, it's always my goal to achieve a certain connection with every guest in order to trust them with my property. So far this approach has resulted in overall satisfaction and quite some new friends. So let me know what your interests are and you will experience Amsterdam feeling like a local instead of a tourist!

name: SWEETS hotel Hortusbrug
description:
Stay in a three-dimensional Mondriaan painting on top of a canal! A true icon in the middle of Amsterdam Centre, perfect for lovers of architecture and design, located in between quaint 17th-century canal houses and Amsterdam’s historic botanical garden ‘Hortus Botanicus’. The white cubical structure with its black, blue and yellow details reminisces of De Stijl and the famous Dutch architect and designer Gerrit Rietveld. Free entrance to Hortus Botanicus included!

The space
From 1956 to 2017, bridge house ‘Hortusbrug’ accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers. In 2017, the bridge house started a new chapter as one of SWEETS hotel’s 28 hotel rooms. As with every SWEET, Hortusbrug’s interior is inspired by its architectural history.

Architect 1956: Dirk Sterenberg
Architect 2017: Space&Matter
Architectural Style: New Objectivity
Waterway: Nieuwe Herengracht
Bridge Type: Bascule bridge

The building appears to float on the
neighborhood_overview: Since your hotel room is in the middle of Amsterdam Center, many must-sees are within walking distance: the Maritime Museum, NEMO Science Museum, the Skinny Bridge, the Hermitage, the vintage market on Waterlooplein… the possibilities are endless. Bookings for bridge house Hortusbrug include a SWEET little extra for plant lovers: free entrance to the beautiful ‘Hortus Botanicus’ next-door. Complete your nature and history-themed day with a visit to Artis Zoo at just a 6-minute walk. Check out our self-composed Neighbourhood Guide on the tablet in the room for more recommendations!
host_about:
SWEETS hotel is a one-of-a-kind hotel located across Amsterdam in 28 different bridge houses. Each bridge house has been transformed into an independent hotel suite that accommodates a maximum of two guests.

For centuries, Amsterdam’s bridge houses accommodated the city’s many bridge keepers who were responsible for opening the impressive structures for passing water traffic. With building dates between 1673 and 2009, the bridge houses carry an extensive history. Visiting them in chronological order is like a journey through time: their various architectural styles reveal how the city developed and grew, when new quarters were built and even how people thought about city development at that time.

With the hotel room interiors, SWEETS hotel offers guests a unique and comfortable living space, while keeping the history of every bridge house in mind. All bridge houses are different, and so are the interiors. Every SWEET accommodates up to two adults and contains a kingsize double bed, a bathroom and coffee and tea facilities.

SWEETS hotel, first initiated in 2012 as an urban space project, is 8 years in the making. Over half of the 28 bridge houses are currently available for reservations, with more coming soon.

SWEETS hotel is an initiative and co-creation of the architecture office Space&Matter (known for De Ceuvel, an ecological hub), project development partner Grayfield and Suzanne Oxenaar and Otto Nan of Seven New Things, founders of Lloyd Hotel & Cultural Embassy (the world’s first 1- to 5-star hotel) and Hotel The Exchange.

In this area you can find most of the city’s famous attractions and sights, such as the Dam Palace, museums, the flower market, 9 Little Streets (9 Straatjes), the red light district, nightlife and still so much more to discover. neighborhood_overview:
Now well-established as the hippest area of Amsterdam (and one of the priciest to live) de Pijp has everything that locals could crave. There’s the beautiful Sarphatipark, bustling Albert Cuypstraat market, and enough shops, bars, cafés and restaurants orbiting those to keep locals and visitors entertained for quite some time.

Originally built for Amsterdam’s workers during the 1800s to ease overpopulation in the Jordaan area, the neighbourhood has been re-purposed in the 21st Century by students, affluent singles and trendy young families who’ve settled in the area. With that, dozens of bars, cafés and boutiques have sprung up to service a population looking for good coffee and unique retail experiences.

But it’s the street market which still provides the heart and soul of the area. Held six days per week for over a century, it’s here, in the concentrated stream of grocery shoppers, that you’ll see a real slice of life with more locals (read ex-pats as well as Am

For your comfort, towels, bed linen and a weekly housekeeping are provided. Some apartments also feature a washing machine and there are public laundry rooms. The Hermitage Museum is just 650 meters away, while Artis Zoo is only 400 meters from Wittenberg. The nearest airport is Schiphol Airport, 12 km away or a 30-minute drive by car.

neighborhood_overview:
This apartment is located in Amsterdam Oost (East), an upcoming, vibrant district of Amsterdam. You won’t see many tourists here, because it’s the place where the locals love to hang when the city centre is too crowded. The apartment is just around the corner from the Linnaeusstraat: a buzzing street with many cool bars like the Biertuin and Kuijper. In the summer you’ll find the hippest Amsterdam crowd on sunny terraces, enjoying a “Brouwerij ‘t IJ’, a beer from the famous local brewery that’s located in a wind mill (also just 10 minutes away from the apartment). The Beukenplein is on the other side of the street; here you’ll find amongst others bars like Bar Bukowski (they serve great gin and tonics!), Maxwell and an amazing pizza place.

For very cheap, fresh food and a real Amsterdam experience you can walk your way up to the Dappermarkt, the multicultural market where locals buy their fruit and vegetables. Make sure to stop by the Oosterpark on the way, an amazing park

name: Amsterdam, Tiny House with incredible view
description:
Newly build (2018), wooden but luxurious tiny house. Private area. A lot of space around your tiny house and a huge field of grass (protected area for birds) in front of your glass doors.

Suitable for couples and friends. Small animals are welcome in consultation.

How does it feel?

If you need a break from your hectic life or want to enjoy the silence after a busy day in Amsterdam, this is an excellent place.
Privacy, comfort and the sound of birds, frogs and very often cows..

The space
Where is it placed?

Durgerdam is in the North of Amsterdam. It has 1 street which actually is a dyke. Dykes were build to protect Holland against high water levels. There is just one street called: Durgerdammerdijk, meaning dyke of Durgerdam. Authentic rural area (former fishermen village), but still close to Amsterdam (city). Easy to reach from Amsterdam Airport Schiphol (23 km), exit S115 'Durgerdam' from A10.

The T
neighborhood_overview:
Most of the visitors (and I absolutely agree) love Durgerdam because you stay in a pristine authentic quiet place, where you can enjoy nature. But just a stone's throw away you will be in the city center of Amsterdam. On your bike or with 15 minutes by car, Uber or a taxi.

For Dutch people: DE TEKST IN HET ENGELS DOET MISSCHIEN VERMOEDEN DAT HET TINY HOUSE VOORAL VOOR BUITENLANDSE GASTEN IS. MAAR ALS JE HOUDT VAN HET HOLLANDSE LANDSCHAP, AMSTERDAM WIL ONTDEKKEN MAAR NIET IN DE HECTIEK WIL SLAPEN EN ONS EIGEN PRACHTIGE NEDERLAND WIL BELEVEN, DAN ZIT JE IN DURGERDAM OP EEN HELE AANGENAME PLEK.

Durgerdam (part of Amsterdam) has 1 lovely restaurant: Zuyderziel, if you don't want to cook yourself. This is 3 minutes walking from the Tiny House. Update: this is in renovation now. Re-opening in 2022. The closest supermarket, that also provides fresh fish, meat, flowers and good vegetarian food is 7 minutes away by bike. In the tiny house there is a book with suggestion
host_about:
How it all started...

In my humble opinion I am very privileged to live in one of the most special places in the world: Durgerdam (Amsterdam - North).  On a historical dyke (former fisherman village), next to the IJsselmeer lake, in the typical Dutch rural landscape, but still very close to the unique city of Amsterdam.

As television producer I did (and do)  travel  a lot and I am always a fan of remarkable, unique accommodations to sleep and to stay in. Especially  excited do I get  when they are placed in the middle of nature or at unique locations.  Inspired by my visits to those spots, I decided to build my own little house, with all the comfort you need on a special place; my hometown Durgerdam/Amsterdam North.

Together with an architect we created the Tiny House. An authentic small wouden house, where I hope a lot of other people feel at home and can enjoy the green area & of course Amsterdam..

Spiegelkwartier

The Spiegelkwartier is the Art and Antiques district in Amsterdam.
Here you’ll find more than 70 antiques dealers and art galleries, together offering a resplendent array of fine historical objects, classic and contemporary art, and exotic folk art.
You will find also restaurants, casual eateries and cosy cafés on almost every corner.
The Spiegelkwartier is located between the Herengracht and the Rijksmuseum.

www.spiegelkwartier.nl

Museum Quarter

The Amsterdam Museum Quarter is home to the three most important museums in the Netherlands: the Rijksmuseum, the Stedelijk Museum and the Van Gogh Museum.
It also houses the majestic Concertgebouw and some superb cafés and restaurants.
With its large grassy open area, the Museumplein offers plenty of room to have a picnic or just relax. The Museum Quarter even has its own indoor swimming pool.

neighborhood_overview:
Zuidas is a high-end international knowledge and business centre that is also one of the most important office locations in the Netherlands.
The Amsterdam forrest (Amsterdamse Bos) is three times the size of New York’s Central Park And entirely man-made. Spanning an impressive 1,000 hectares, the Amsterdamse Bos is among the largest city parks of Europe.
The Olympic stadium, the Olympic games of 1928 were held here and still hosting numerous sportive/cultural events.
VU (Vrije Universiteit) and VU academic hospital are one of the most well known university and hospital of the country.
Two large high-end indoor shopping malls are within 10min by bus.
host_about:
I was born and raised in South Korea and I spent last 25 years in several European countries. so I had a great opportunity to live in two completely different parts of the world. 

Since I got married with my Dutch husband and got two children I don’t travel as frequently as I used to do but I enjoy meeting new friendly people and visiting new destinations any time I can.

host_about:
I am a realtor since 20 years. Some of my hobbies are travelling,  Ibiza, (race) cycling, my work, cars, soccer and my close friends and family. 

We started this company 20 years ago. In April 2013 we started with renting out through Airbnb. With our experience in letting out to expats from the biggest Multinationals (Shell/Unilever/Johnson&Johnson) we know what people expect in a temporary apartment. 

We try to develop our apartments in a tasteful neutral style with high quality finishing and - furniture on nice locations like the Amsterdam Jordaan Area. Our apartments are not on the busiest places of Amsterdam but always on a maximum 3 minute walk from the canals. 

All our (Amsterdam)apartments are fully licensed by town hall what means that safety is on place 1. Infrared smoke detectors, flight plans, not too many people in 1 flat, no drugs etc.

We try to offer a hotel idea but than in an apartment. So more privacy, luxury, convenience and space on a AAA location but for a better price!

A definite no go is asking for a discount. If our prices are too high I would suggest to rent a bed where the owner was in the night before. 

Also we dont accept guests without any reviews. No exceptions. Sorry.


What is also convenient in our opinion is that we do not live our selves in the apartments. So You dont  sleep on a bed where someone has slept on for 5 years already.

please see our reviews for confirmation if you are not convinced yet!

neighborhood_overview:
Home to some of the world’s best art museums, Oud-Zuid (Old-South) is one of Amsterdam’s most elegant and well-heeled neighbourhoods, where impressive manors line leafy streets, and chic boutiques abound. From the splendour of Museumplein to the vibrant Vondelpark and the serene boulevards of Willemspark, the beautiful neighbourhood of Oud-Zuid rewards the visitor at every turn.

Just outside the cultural heart of Amsterdam lies the posh neighbourhood of Oud-Zuid, with its ravishing villas and tranquil curving streets. The Oud-Zuid is arguably the elegant heart of Amsterdam, and is definitly the city’s most prestigious cultural district.

Amsterdam’s elegant Oud-Zuid (Old-South) was developed over a century ago as a cultural gateway to the city, at the tip of what was previously a boggy polder. It’s home to Rijksmuseum, Stedelijk Museum, and Van Gogh Museum – all of which exhibit the highlights of Western art. The nearby Vondelpark – created in the style of an Engl
